g.text: Alain: "What the fuck does the kitchen have to do with this?" The tattooed man does not understand.
Shanky: "While you're in there -- make fatty a snack." He grins. "Can't you hear how his stomach is growling?!"
Visual Calculus: It's close enough to the latch up there -- one can slide it open and just take it. Surely not a coincidence.
You: "Someone's hid a key in the bush." (Point at the window.)
Titus Hardie: "It's an older building -- who knows?" He shrugs.
Empathy: The shrug is disingenuous. He's intrigued -- if only for a moment.
Kim Kitsuragi: "It *could* open the door in the kitchen -- the blue door." He looks at the key in your hand. "It says 'Workshop, Spare' -- maybe there's a workshop there?"
Empathy: It's said without aggression -- as genuine advice.
Conceptualization: It's not a very good mother-joke, but the room still laughs. Something about those mother-jokes just *works*.
Perception (Sight): Nothing, as before. Just black branches.
Shanky: "What's this weirdo cop doing now, huh? Window-shopping?"
Visual Calculus: You see two, maybe three bushes, grown into a single thicket -- over a period of circa 50 years. It takes time for a hedge like that to form.
Theo: "Off yourself -- make it up to me, cop. I still got my money on that."
Authority: There is a silence around this man's words -- unlike Titus, they're *afraid* of him. That's the type of respect he commands.
You: "I need your guys to hand the key to me."
Shanky: "And *I* need the fatty to get his feet amputated 'cause the smell is killing me -- we can't always get what we want."
Theo: The key is brass. 'Workshop, Spare' is etched into its bow. The old man closes the window and sits back down in silence.
Kim Kitsuragi: "It's for the blue door in the kitchen -- the note inside said the workshop key is behind the window. This is that key." He makes a note in his blue notebook.
Kim Kitsuragi: "It's for the blue door in the kitchen. There was a note there that you missed. It said the workshop key is behind the window. It's this key." He makes a note in his blue notebook.
Cafeteria Window: There's a little slide panel up there, to let some air in. No need to open it in spring. It's still too cold outside.
Theo: "Don't thank me." The old man takes out his pack of chewing tobacco. "I don't give two shits about your key."
Glen: "Why did she put it *back*? After she took it?"
Shanky: "Look at Glenny and his girlfriend!"
Glen: "Boss, I don't want to make excuses for her, but..." He stops.
Perception (Sight): There's a yellow ribbon tied to one of the branches -- light yellow, faded with time. A tiny splash of colour in the blackness of the thicket. Hanging from it -- a bronze key.
Logic: Someone hid the key in the bush and attached a yellow ribbon to make it easier to find.
You: (Look at the key in your hand.) "I wonder what doors does it open?"
Visual Calculus: The kitchen -- the only part of the building you haven't thoroughly searched yet.
Theo: With a loud thud the old man stands up -- pushes the window open -- grabs the key from the hawthorn branch and slides it across the table to you.
Theo: "I'm tired of listening to your shit."
Visual Calculus: One can't see into the Union box from the yard *outside* -- that hawthorn is too thick.
Shanky: "Wow, no. I hadn't heard that."
Alain: "Yeah -- because they like to sniff around in *dirt*." The tattooed man gives you a look.
Titus Hardie: "It's an older building -- who knows?" He shrugs.
You: "Thank you." (Nod to the old man.)
Kim Kitsuragi: "There was a barred door on the roof that did *not* have a lock -- perhaps there is one *downstairs* that does?" He looks around. "We should search the *kitchen*."
Alain: "I think he's trying to find dirt on us, in our box. It's what they do, Shanks. Did you know policemen are sometimes called *pigs*?"
Titus Hardie: "Didn't even know it was there..." The man looks at the key in your hand -- then around the room. "Boys?"
Kim Kitsuragi: "If he says it's there, it's there." The lieutenant takes his glasses off to clean them -- then puts them back on.
Glen: "Sorry, Fucko! These *guys* won't help you. Looks like you're gonna have to go bush-diving. The hawthorn's got a bitch of a bite!"
Shanky: "I'm gonna enjoy the sight of you in the bushes out there..."
Cafeteria Window: Behind the dockworkers: a ceiling height window. The hawthorn branches scrape the glass like bony fingers.
Inland Empire: The men are talking, but you swear you hear those black limbs tap on the window as the wind blows outside.
Empathy: The shrug is disingenuous. He's intrigued -- if only for a moment.
Titus Hardie: "A little wisdom from old Titus -- not everything is connected to one thing. Keys just lie around. It's a messy world."
Perception (Sight): Nothing, as always. By now you're almost certain there may be a sparrow's nest on one of the branches.
You: "Maybe this is somehow connected to Ruby getting to the roof?"
Titus Hardie: "Your secret route theory?" He shakes his head. "You're grasping for straws, cop-man. Why'd she put it back if it's hers?"
Logic: He's just trying to sound clever. He has no idea what you're looking for -- nor do you, yourself.
Titus Hardie: "Wild theory, cop-man. The worst thing is -- I like it. She's been in this box plenty of times. This would give her access to the workshop route."

Perception (Sight): Nothing. Even though you *know* you should see it -- you don't. Just branches like black tangles of hair. Motionless. The wind in the yard doesn't reach the hawthorn. Maybe come back later and you can try again?
Perception (Sight): Nothing. Just black tangles like the hair of an old woman. Motionless. The wind in the yard doesn't reach the hawthorn, nor does the light come in from this window.

Kim Kitsuragi: "It says... 'Workshop, Spare'." He looks at the key in your hand. "There's a door in the *kitchen* that caught my eye yesterday -- it's very *blue*. Maybe there's a workshop behind it?"
Titus Hardie: "Huh?" The big guy looks behind him.
You: "Does anyone know why this key was hanging right outside the Union box window?"
You: "Maybe this is how Ruby got to the roof that night? Using this key."
Inland Empire: It wasn't time yet. You have to know of the girl... Return when you know more.
Perception (Hearing): You can and it's pretty terrifying.
Titus Hardie: "It's a solid point, Shanks. There's a lot of things off about pinning this on Ruby. Be careful when you find her, cop -- be *fair*. Give her a chance to defend herself."
Empathy: It's said without aggression. In good trust.
Visual Calculus: Yes. The nest of a common house sparrow. Passer domesticus.
Titus Hardie: "It's an older building -- who knows?" He shrugs.
Fat Angus: "That's not even funny, Dennis."
Titus Hardie: "I'm not your janitor, cop." He glances at the window. "I don't even know what you're talking about. There's nothing there."
Titus Hardie: "It's an older building -- who knows?" He shrugs.
Cafeteria Window: Again you find yourself looking at that big old window...
Inland Empire: Keep at it. There must be a reason you've looked out this window so many times.
You: "Can you let me slide by so I can grab the thing?"
Alain: "I don't know about that..." The tattooed man yawns and settles more comfortably on the bench. "I'm comfortable here... don't think any sliding would really help right now."
Glen: "C'mon, man. We were just having some fun! Where's the harm in...?"
Visual Calculus: The kitchen -- the only part of the building you haven't thoroughly searched yet. It's worth a try!
Glen: "Sorry, Fucko! Looks like you're gonna have to go bush-diving. Good fucking luck with that -- the hawthorn's got a bitch of a bite!"
You: "Titus, can you hand the key to me please?"
Fat Angus: "Goddamnit, Dennis. You know I can't help it!" His whiny voice is in deep contrast with his stature.
Eugene: "Never even seen it. Someone must have hidden it there before this room became our place."
Inland Empire: You're not so sure about that. Somehow you just *know* -- there's something out there, behind the glass.
